BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:pmJtZiubK4xD5n7Y85cFD
SUMMARY:Susan Meiselas: Crossings
DTSTAMP:20260205T082822Z
DTSTART:20260205T200000Z
DESCRIPTION:First presented at the Art Institute of Chicago in 1990\, this 
	exhibition by Susan Meiselas intertwines documentary photographs of Centra
	l America during the 1970s and 1980s \\(from Nicaragua and El Salvador\\) 
	along with panoramic images from the US/Mexico border taken in 1989. Addit
	ional photographs of the US/Mexico border taken in 2018 are also featured 
	in a site-specific gallery installation. The exhibition invites viewers to
	 see immigration in the context of economic and political crises in the re
	gion.\n\nToday\, the work feels newly urgent. US immigration enforcement h
	as expanded through militarization and constant surveillance\, with leader
	s using fear-driven language to divide communities and legitimize brutal f
	orms of control.\n\nThese photographs ask us to look carefully\, to recogn
	ize familiar patterns\, and to hold on to our shared humanity across the g
	lobe. People move in search of safety\, possibility\, and a better life fo
	r their families\, which is a universal hope that crosses borders\, genera
	tions\, and time.
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/susan-meiselas-crossings/
	17977024/2026-02-05T00
LOCATION:Photographic Center Northwest (PCNW)\, 900 12th Ave.\, Seattle\, W
	A
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT9H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:GIXvbjZslznspSFtzHLm_
SUMMARY:Faculty Scholarship Symposium
DTSTAMP:20260205T082822Z
DTSTART:20260205T200000Z
DESCRIPTION:ENGAGED SCHOLARSHIP AND ACADEMIC FREEDOM\n\n \n\nPlease join co
	lleagues for the annual Faculty Scholarship Symposium hosted by the Office
	 of the Provost in partnership with the ORSP\, Center for Faculty Developm
	ent\, Center for Community Engagement\, Office of Undergraduate Research\,
	 Office of Research Oversight/Institutional Review Board\, and Lemieux Lib
	rary. Our focus this year is elevating our unique scholarship strengths in
	 a climate of increasing political and culture threat to academic research
	\, teaching\, and freedom. This event will showcase the extensive resource
	s and opportunities available to faculty in support of scholarly activitie
	s and participants will have an opportunity to discuss areas of success an
	d to recommend additional forms of support and initiatives.\n\n \n\nThe Fa
	culty Scholarship Symposium will feature stories and examples of faculty s
	cholarship that engages communities\, industries\, policy-makers\, and the
	 general public. Please take a few minutes to update your information here
	: Faculty Scholarship Database\n\n \n\nFor those attending remotely\, the 
	Zoom link will be sent out the day prior to the event.\n\nA detailed agend
